<dl id="n53094e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53094e">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53094e"> 94(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Arth Mac Utther ~ <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53094e"><li>FW 275.09 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ld/lexld.htm#n53094e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ld/l39ld.htm#n53094e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53094e">MS BL 47478-337</ms> </li><li>JJA 53:316 <a name="lad13" href="../../FF/fdra/lda.htm#ldd3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ld/ldd3.htm#n53094e">Draft: II.2&sect;5.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">These places are unheard of in the Welsh Arthurian tales, but, according to Geoffrey, it was at Dimilioc that Uther besieged, and his men slew, Gorlois; and it was this siege that enabled <mark>Uther</mark>, in the semblance of Gorlois, to gain access to Igerne in her retreat at the castle of Tintagel, and so to become <mark>the father of</mark> &ldquo;the most renowned <mark>Arthur</mark>.&rdquo; <small> W. Lewis Jones, <a name="WJKA3" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WJKA3"><cite title="source">King Arthur in History and Legend</cite></a> (1914) 57</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
